In article <C6Kw5r.84w@news.claremont.edu>, ebrandt@jarthur.claremont.edu (Eli Brandt) writes:
>For the voice-phone application, the incoming data will be highly
>compressed in any case; even a bad system would probably leave it
>indistinguishable from pre-encrypted data.  The chip could in theory
>check to see whether the voice compression format is correct on input
>data, and broadcast the result, but 1) this would be visible
>evidence of "hidden features", and 2) the chip doesn't *know* the
>voice compression to be used.

